## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Camera Always-On Requirement**: For presence detection to work, the camera must be running continuously. The current UX requires the user to manually toggle the camera on. The plan changes this so the camera **auto-starts** when the page loads. The floating camera widget becomes always-visible (but still draggable/resizable/closeable).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Wake Word Kept as Fallback**: The wake word ("Hey Jarvis") will still work as a secondary activation method. Both coexist — whichever triggers first wins.

> [!WARNING]
> **New Dependency: `mediapipe`** (~30MB). Runs purely on CPU with no GPU requirement. First inference takes ~200-500ms (model load), subsequent ones ~10-30ms. Very lightweight for your CPU-compatible setup.

## How It Works

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Client as Browser (Camera)
    participant WS as WebSocket
    participant Server as Python Server
    participant MP as MediaPipe Face Detection

    Note over Client: Camera auto-starts on page load
    
    loop Every 1.5s while PASSIVE
        Client->>WS: { type: "presence_frame", image_b64: "..." }
        WS->>Server: Forward frame
        Server->>MP: detect_face(frame)
        MP-->>Server: face_detected: true/false, face_size_ratio: 0.18
        
        alt Face detected & large enough (2+ consecutive frames)
            Server->>WS: { type: "person_detected" }
            WS->>Client: Trigger wake-up UI feedback
            Note over Server: Mode → PROCESSING → speaks greeting
        else No face or too small
            Note over Server: Reset consecutive count to 0
        end
    end
    
    Note over Server: Normal conversation flow continues...
    
    Note over Server: When session ends → back to PASSIVE
    Note over Client: Resume sending presence frames
```

