## Configuration Summary

All tunable via environment variables in `.env`:

| Variable | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `PRESENCE_DETECT_CONFIDENCE` | `0.5` | MediaPipe minimum detection confidence (0.0-1.0) |
| `PRESENCE_MIN_FACE_RATIO` | `0.02` | Minimum face-area / frame-area ratio (~15% of frame width) |
| `PRESENCE_CONFIRM_FRAMES` | `2` | Consecutive positive detections before activation |
| `PRESENCE_FRAME_COOLDOWN` | `5.0` | Seconds to wait after activation before accepting new presence frames |

## Open Questions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Frame Send Interval**: Currently planned at **1.5 seconds**. Faster (1s) = more responsive but more CPU/bandwidth. Slower (2s) = less responsive but lighter. What feels right for your reception desk setup?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Consecutive Frames Threshold**: Currently **2 consecutive positive detections** (~3 seconds total) before activation. Higher = more cautious (fewer false triggers), Lower = more responsive. Your preference?

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
- Run the server and verify MediaPipe model loads without errors via `warmup_mediapipe()`
- Send a test `presence_frame` over WebSocket and verify detection response in logs
- Verify wake word still works alongside presence detection (both coexist)
- Test with no face in frame → verify no false activation

### Manual Verification  
1. Open the client page → camera should auto-start immediately
2. Stand in front of the camera → AIRA should activate within ~3 seconds and speak the greeting
3. Walk away and come back → AIRA should re-activate after the cooldown period
4. Walk past quickly → AIRA should NOT trigger (single frame, need 2 consecutive)
5. Stand far away → AIRA should NOT trigger (face too small, below `MIN_FACE_RATIO`)
6. Say "Hey Jarvis" without being on camera → should still work as fallback
7. During an active conversation → presence frames should NOT be processed (mode ≠ PASSIVE)
